I actually was stuck in the same problem for a week but I figured it out. I know it is an old question, but wanted to leave my solution for those who still struggled in 2023 like me.

When you throw the SOAPFault `throw new SOAPFaultException(fault)`, it will use SOAP&#39;s default XML to return the fault. And for some reason that efault XML lets you modify the fault string but not the fault code, thus why in console it says you modified the SOAPFault, but the rendered SOAPFaultException will have no change as it will try to stick with the default SOAP XML, thus your case. 

The solution is to make your CustomException class, and making a class that extends AbstractSoapFaultDefinitionExceptionResolver, so that when Spring WS observes the CustomException thrown, then it uses the custom resolver. 

So you will need two classes, CustomException:
```java
  public class CustomException extends Exception {
}
```
and the exception resolver:

```java
public class ExceptionResolver extends AbstractSoapFaultDefinitionExceptionResolver {

    @Override
    protected SoapFaultDefinition getFaultDefinition(Object endpoint, Exception ex) {
        if (ex instanceof CustomException) {
            // do something
        }
    }
    @Override
    protected void customizeFault(Object endpoint, Exception ex, SoapFault fault) {
        if (ex instanceof CustomException) {
            CustomException customException = ((CustomException) ex);
            try {
                     // customize your fault message
                } catch (Exception e) {
                    throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Error customizing&quot;, e);
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

and then in webservice.config, let Spring know to use this resolver
```java
    @Bean(name = &quot;soapFaultAnnotationExceptionResolver&quot;)
    public ExceptionResolver exceptionResolver() {
        return new ExceptionResolver();
    }
```

You might have to enable the allow-bean-definition-overriding option if it hasn&#39;t been already.

Hopefully this helps anyone struggling!

